{"key":"processedPost-9868479","value":{"id":9868479,"first":9868174,"last":18953568,"when":1235667145,"utime":"02/26/09 06:52 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />yes i have been using a torch lighter and changing my scalpel blades between species</blockquote><br />Not necessary.&nbsp; I use the same scalpel blade until it gets so dull I can't get the cultures to release.<br />It sounds like you're swiping too many spores.&nbsp; If the print is dry, the bacteria should be dead.&nbsp; All you need to do is flame the inoculating loop(NOT scalpel) dip it in agar to cool, and then touch your print and then swipe it on the plate.&nbsp; You'll get plenty of spores that way.&nbsp; If you try to get a lot of spores, you also get a lot of contaminants.&nbsp; Always work right against the flowhood, in the very center.&nbsp; Don't work the edges, and never open a petri dish that is more than 1\" from the face of the flowhood.<br />RR","title":"Re: bacteria with my flowhood"}}